snippet: Conservative factions that already dominate the Parliament seemed to be cruising to victory Friday in a second round of elections to the 290-member assembly.
abstract: Election officials in Iran report a high voter turnout in runoff parliamentary elections, following a nationwide vote in which the conservatives won a resounding victory; outcome is not expected to provide much, if any, comfort for Pres Mahmoud Ahmadinejad, who had a rocky relationship with the departing Parliament. (M)/

byline.original: By THOMAS ERDBRINK; Ramtin Rastin contributed reporting

lead_paragraph: TEHRAN -- Conservative factions that already dominate Parliament here seemed to be cruising to victory on Friday in a second round of elections to the 290-member assembly. The runoff election followed a nationwide vote on March 2, in which the conservatives won a resounding victory when more reform-minded candidates either chose not to participate or were ruled ineligible by a vetting council appointed by Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, and Parliament. That outcome was not expected to be affected by Friday's voting.

headline.main: Iranians Vote In a Runoff For Parliament
